channel.description:
[b]Learn How To Modify You're Server Here (The Basics)[/b]
[i]Welcome!  Here, I'm going to try and explain to you, how to modify/add simple things to you're source.  Once you've read all of this, you should be able to create a half decent server.  Now, I'm not going to go into the meanings of things, such as booleans, voids and why they are here, but I'll show you how to add them/modify them and other things too![/i]

[u][b]Chapters[/b][/u]

[ul][li][i]Starting Off![/i][/li]
[li][i]Modifying the Important .Java Files[/i][/li]
[li][i]Modifying .CFG Files - Coming Soon[/i][/li][/ul]


[b]Requirments[/b]
[i]A source file and some patience.[/i]

[b]Starting Off![/b]
[i]Ok, to start off, simply double-click you're source file, be it Testscape, Pimpscape, whatever.  You should see a bunch of files, some .txt and some .cfg, whereas some are just documents.  There are .class files aswell but we won't get into those.  

Now, the .txt files are named .Java files, these are easy to recognise, just a small notepad icon.

The .CFG files are named .CFG files, these are very easy to recognise, they have 4 small squares for an icon, blue, yellow, red and green.

The documents are usually used for things that are directed through the server, into a file, such as the Character file, once a character logs in, their file automatically saved to the Character file.

The .class files are files that you cannot access, these have been created after the .java files have been compiled.  Just ignore those.

Now, when you first download a server you wan't to rename it, this is one of the most simple jobs of all.  You will understand how to do this by reading the next chapter[/i] : [b]Modifying .Java Files[/b]

[b]Modifying .Java Files[/b]
[i]In this chapter, I'll show you how to add/modify basic things in .Java files, this can be tricky, so be carefull.  

Now, the source I like to use, is the Phonescape source, (V1) it's what I've been working with since day 1, it's important that you use a source that you're comfertable with.  Now, this may be different from you're source but nevertheless, you should pay attention.  I'll explain to my best ability what each .Java files are for and how to modify/add things to them.

First off, antilag.Java.

If you go into you're antilag.Java, you should see something like this.[/i]

[code]// This resets server every 30 mins to stop lag - xerozcheez
import java.io.*;

public class antilag
{

public int ResetTimer = 0;

public void resetserver()
{
misc.println("RESETING SERVER!!!");
misc.println("Saving all games...");
PlayerHandler.kickAllPlayers = true;
misc.println("GAME SUCCESSFULLY SAVED FOR ALL PLAYERS");
ResetTimer = 0;
closeListener();
runserver();
}
public void process()
{
ResetTimer += 1;
if(ResetTimer >= 999999)
{
resetserver();
}
}

public void runserver()
{
  try 
{
String run = "runserver.bat";
String xstr = "./"+run;
Runtime.getRuntime().exec(xstr);
} 
catch (IOException ioe) 
{
	 ioe.printStackTrace();
} 
}

public void closeListener()
{
		try {
			server.shutdownClientHandler = true;
			if(server.clientListener != null) server.clientListener.close();
			server.clientListener = null;
		} 
catch(java.lang.Exception __ex) 
{
			__ex.printStackTrace();
}
}
}[/code]

[i]Now, this is basically for reseting you're server, to prevent lag.  (The longer you're server has been running, the more lag it will have)  To make use of it, simply change the timer in this part of the void.[/i]

[code]if(ResetTimer >= 999999)[/code]

[i]The smaller the number, the more often you're server will reset/restart.  This gets rid of most of the lag for the players and in some cases, you.  I'm not too sure, but I think the time is based on milliseconds.  So every 1000 (1 Thousand) is one second.  I'm not sure about this though.  You can also change the message it sends before and after the  reset/restart.[/i]

[code]misc.println("RESETING SERVER!!!");
misc.println("Saving all games...");
PlayerHandler.kickAllPlayers = true;
misc.println("GAME SUCCESSFULLY SAVED FOR ALL PLAYERS");[/code]

[i]You could change it to something like this.[/i]

[code]misc.println("The server is : Restarting, please wait.");
misc.println("Saving all games...");
PlayerHandler.kickAllPlayers = true;
misc.println("You're account has been saved succesfully, thank-you for you're patience.");[/code]

[i]Now, lets move on to the next .Java file, client.Java.

This file is the most important .Java file in you're source, this contains most of the things you'll be able to modify, which I'm about to explain.

Remember I said something about renaming the server?  This is the place to do it!  All you need to do, is search for the source file name, E.G : Phonescape, Evilscape, Testscape, Pawnagescape, etc.  To search in a .Java file, (I suggest using Notepad) simply hold in Ctrl and then press F (Ctrl+F).  A small window should pop up, you can now use this to search for things you wan't to modify/delete.

Like I said above, you can usually modify the server name by searching for it, so why don't you?  Just type it in.  These are the things you will usually find in sources.[/i]

